    • mergeIidMapsAllowingOverlapOnSimilarItemsOnly

      public static <V> IidMap<V> mergeIidMapsAllowingOverlapOnSimilarItemsOnly​(java.util.Iterator<IidMap<V>> mapsIterator, java.util.function.BiPredicate<V,​V> itemsAreSimilar)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. Throws if a key appears in more than one map, unless the items we are trying to insert are 'similar' (based on the predicate passed in). Since this similarity is not the same as equality, this means that if e.g. the first IidMap maps STOCK_A to money(100), the second one (in the iterator) maps STOCK_A to money(100 + 1e-9), and the third one to money(100 - 1e-9), and similarity is 'values similar to an epsilon of 1e-8', then the resulting IidMap will show money(100) in the final value for STOCK_A, NOT money(100 + 1e-9) or money(100 - 1e-9)

      @SafeVarargs public static <V> IidMap<V> mergeIidMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, IidMap<V> first, IidMap<V> second, IidMap<V>... rest)

    • mergeIidMapsByTransformedEntry

      public static <V,​ V1,​ V2> IidMap<V> mergeIidMapsByTransformedEntry​(TriFunction<InstrumentId,​V1,​V2,​V> mergeFunction, java.util.function.BiFunction<InstrumentId,​V1,​V> onlyLeftPresent, java.util.function.BiFunction<InstrumentId,​V2,​V> onlyRightPresent, IidMap<V1> leftMap, IidMap<V2> rightMap)
      Merges two maps into a single one, but also transforms the values into a possibly different type. For the 3 separate cases of a key appearing in the left map / right map / both maps, modify the values based on the functions passed in. This is similar to mergeIidMapsByValue, except that it applies: - in cases where the maps have different types in their values - for two maps only It is also similar to mergeRBMapsByTransformedValue, but it applies to IidMaps (not RBMaps), and also it allows the two input maps to have values of different types.
      See Also:
      mergeIidMapsByTransformedValue(java.util.function.BiFunction<V1, V2, V>, java.util.function.Function<V1, V>, java.util.function.Function<V2, V>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.IidMap<V1>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.IidMap<V2>), RBMapMergers.mergeRBMapsByTransformedValue(java.util.function.BiFunction<K, java.util.List<V1>, V2>, java.util.List<com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMap<K, V1>>)

    • mergeThreeIidMapsByTransformedEntry

      public static <V,​ V1,​ V2,​ V3> IidMap<V> mergeThreeIidMapsByTransformedEntry​(QuadriFunction<InstrumentId,​java.util.Optional<V1>,​java.util.Optional<V2>,​java.util.Optional<V3>,​V> mergeFunction, IidMap<V1> map1, IidMap<V2> map2, IidMap<V3> map3)
      Merges three maps into a single one, but also transforms the values into a possibly different type. Unlike mergeIidMapsByTransformedEntry, there are too many cases of keys having values or not (2 ^ 3 - 1) to handle with separate lambdas. Therefore, we'll handle all of these with a lambda that takes optionals based on whether values exist or not, for each respective map.
      See Also:
      mergeIidMapsByTransformedValue(java.util.function.BiFunction<V1, V2, V>, java.util.function.Function<V1, V>, java.util.function.Function<V2, V>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.IidMap<V1>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.IidMap<V2>)

    • mergeIidMapsByTransformedValue

      public static <V,​ V1,​ V2> IidMap<V> mergeIidMapsByTransformedValue​(java.util.function.BiFunction<V1,​V2,​V> mergeFunction, java.util.function.Function<V1,​V> onlyLeftPresent, java.util.function.Function<V2,​V> onlyRightPresent, IidMap<V1> leftMap, IidMap<V2> rightMap)
      Just like mergeIidMapsByTransformedEntry, except that the lambdas you pass in don't take the key in as a parameter. This is a simpler alternative for those cases where your transformations do not rely on the map key.

    • mergeThreeIidMapsByTransformedValue

      public static <V,​ V1,​ V2,​ V3> IidMap<V> mergeThreeIidMapsByTransformedValue​(TriFunction<java.util.Optional<V1>,​java.util.Optional<V2>,​java.util.Optional<V3>,​V> mergeFunction, IidMap<V1> map1, IidMap<V2> map2, IidMap<V3> map3)
      Just like mergeIidMapsByTransformedEntry, except that the lambdas you pass in don't take the key in as a parameter. This is a simpler alternative for those cases where your transformations do not rely on the map key.

    • mergeIidMapsByValue

      public static <V> IidMap<V> mergeIidMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, java.util.stream.Stream<IidMap<V>> mapsStream)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. In the event a key appears in more than one map, apply a binary operator (e.g. '+') to merge the values. This doesn't *assume* that the operator is commutative, but it probably should be. Otherwise, your result will depend on the order you pass the maps in the stream, which will be confusing.

    • mergeIidMapsByTransformedValue

      public static <V1,​ V2> IidMap<V2> mergeIidMapsByTransformedValue​(java.util.function.BiFunction<InstrumentId,​java.util.List<V1>,​V2> mergeFunction, java.util.List<IidMap<V1>> mapsList)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. This is similar to the previous overload, except that it allows you to merge multiple (and possibly 0) items at a time, plus the value in the returned map doesn't have to be of the same type as the input maps. This is particularly useful for cases where it is more computationally expensive (or numerically unstable) to merge N items 2 at a time (as with the previous overload) vs. merging them all together.

    • mergeIidMapsByValue

      public static <V> IidMap<V> mergeIidMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> onlyLeftPresent, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> onlyRightPresent, IidMap<V> leftMap, IidMap<V> rightMap)
      Merges two maps into a single one. For the 3 separate cases of a key appearing in the left map / right map / both maps, modify the values based on the functions passed in.

    • mergeIidMapsInOrderAllowingOverwriting

      @SafeVarargs public static <V> IidMap<V> mergeIidMapsInOrderAllowingOverwriting​(IidMap<V> first, IidMap<V> second, IidMap<V>... rest)
      It is rare that we overwrite map entries, but sometimes we want to merge maps in the order they are supplied.

      This returns a map whose keys are the set union of the keys in the maps supplied, and corresponding value for every such key is the value for the latest map in the arguments supplied.
